00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.750
for molecular orbitals.

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:27.690
So molecular orbital
theory presents the idea

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:30.210
that these valence
electrons are really

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:33.540
going to be delocalized
around these molecules

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:37.280
and not just sitting
on individual atoms.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:40.470
So to think about this
electron do localization,

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:43.410
we need to think about
molecular orbitals.

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:46.380
Molecular orbitals,
as we've learned,

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:48.710
another word for orbital
is also wave functions.

00:04:48.710 --> 00:04:49.960
Wave functions are orbitals.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:51.700
Orbitals are wave functions.

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:54.570
You need to consider
the wavelike properties

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:57.320
of electrons to think about
where the electrons are going

00:04:57.320 --> 00:04:59.830
to be, what is their
probability density,

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:01.540
how are they going
to be arranged

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:03.900
with respect to the nucleus.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.130
And so when we take
atomic orbitals

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:09.130
and we bring them together
as atoms come together

00:05:09.130 --> 00:05:11.640
to form bonds, atomic
orbitals come together

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:13.510
to form molecular orbitals.

00:05:13.510 --> 00:05:17.430
So we're going to be adding
superimposing, atomic orbitals

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:21.400
to form these
molecular orbitals.

00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:26.480
And this is called a linear
combination of atomic orbitals,

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:29.380
or LCAO.

00:05:29.380 --> 00:05:32.370
And so we're going to bring
those atomic orbitals together

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:34.240
and create molecular orbitals.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:36.770
And we're going to create two
types of molecular orbitals.

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:40.380
We're going to create
bonding and antibonding.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:44.220
And some basic math
principles apply here,

00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:51.480
and that is that you can
create N molecular orbitals

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:54.821
from N atomic orbitals.

00:05:54.821 --> 00:05:55.320
All right.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:58.810
So that's really the basis
of molecular orbital theory,

00:05:58.810 --> 00:06:04.650
and now let's apply it to
our friends, the s orbitals.

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:05.150
All right.

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.400
So we're going to think about
really simple molecules,

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:10.720
bringing together two atoms that
are identical with each other

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:14.790
and what happens to their s
orbitals when this happens.

00:06:14.790 --> 00:06:19.410
So first we'll talk
about bonding orbitals.

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:21.700
So bonding orbitals,
again, arise

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:26.930
from this linear combination
of atomic orbitals, the LCAO.

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:28.750
And if it's a
bonding orbital, it's

00:06:28.750 --> 00:06:31.970
going to arise from
constructive interference.

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:35.520
So we talked before about the
properties of waves, and one

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:37.720
of the great
properties of waves is

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:40.550
that they can constructively
interfere, destructively

00:06:40.550 --> 00:06:41.710
interfere.

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:45.120
And orbitals are wave functions
so they can constructively

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.000
interfere and
destructively interfere.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.100
Bonding orbitals
are generated by

00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:52.550
the constructive interference.

00:06:52.550 --> 00:06:55.510
So let's look at
two atomic orbitals.

00:06:55.510 --> 00:06:56.850
And so here we have an orbital.

00:06:56.850 --> 00:06:58.360
The nucleus is in the middle.

00:06:58.360 --> 00:06:59.120
It's a little dot.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:00.310
It's a nucleus.

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:03.070
And these two atomic orbitals
are going to come together.

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:05.060
There's going to
be a bonding event.

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:09.280
And so we have a 1s
orbital from atom a

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:12.440
and a 1s orbital from
atom b, and they're

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:14.280
going to come
together, and they're

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:16.380
going to form a
molecular orbital,

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:23.430
an ab molecular orbital,
and this is called sigma 1s.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:30.110
So a sigma orbital is
symmetric around the bond axis,

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:34.800
so the bond axis here would
be just a vertical, a line

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:37.660
between these two nuclei here.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:42.620
And so this molecular orbital
is symmetric around that bond

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:43.600
axis.

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:47.250
There are no nodal planes for
something that is symmetric.

00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:51.870
There are no nodal planes
for our s orbitals,

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:55.500
and so there's none for the
molecular orbital either.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:08:02.000
And we can also write
this as 1sa plus 1sb.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:06.830
So the atomic orbital from 1sa,
the atomic orbital 1sb coming

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:10.150
together to form
sigma orbital 1s.

00:08:10.150 --> 00:08:12.830
That is a bonding
orbital because it's

00:08:12.830 --> 00:08:14.900
constructive interference.

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:18.610
It's a bonding MO,
or molecular orbital.

00:08:18.610 --> 00:08:21.830
So now let's consider
the wavelike properties

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:24.930
and think about these atomic
orbitals coming together

00:08:24.930 --> 00:08:28.590
as waves in what is happening.

00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:32.090
So here we have the
same equation up here.

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:35.600
We're bringing
together 1sa and 1sb,

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:38.530
but now let's think about
this as a wave function.

00:08:38.530 --> 00:08:40.830
So there is an
amplitude associated

00:08:40.830 --> 00:08:45.370
with the wave function
for 1sa, and there

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:50.760
is an amplitude associated
with the wave function for 1sb.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:52.630
These wave functions
come together.

00:08:52.630 --> 00:08:56.130
Here is one nuclei,
here's the other nuclei.

00:08:56.130 --> 00:08:58.700
And for a bonding
orbital, it will

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:03.270
be constructive interference,
and so the amplitude

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:07.630
where these atomic
wave functions overlap

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:11.120
will be increased when you
have constructive interference.

00:09:11.120 --> 00:09:14.600
So our sigma 1s
now has increased

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:17.980
amplitude between
these two nuclei

00:09:17.980 --> 00:09:22.180
due to that constructive
interference.

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:26.270
So an increased amplitude
between these two nuclei,

00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:28.800
again, this is the bonding
axis-- here is one nuclei, here

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:33.060
is another-- so an
increased amplitude here

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:37.720
corresponds to an increased or
enhanced probability density.

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:41.360
Remember our wave function
squared is probability density.

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:43.270
It suggests the
likelihood of finding

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:47.660
an electron in a
certain region of volume

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.970
and if it's enhanced by this
constructive interference.

00:09:51.970 --> 00:09:56.500
So if that probability
density is enhanced,

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.380
you have a greater
chance of finding

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:02.350
an electron between these
two nuclei, which will

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:05.000
be attracted by both nuclei.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.160
So now why don't
you tell me what

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:10.150
you think is going to
happen to an electron that

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:14.360
is in this region of
constructive interference,

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:17.568
this increased area of
probability density.

00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:33.045
OK, 10 more seconds.

00:10:48.540 --> 00:10:49.440
Interesting.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:55.080
OK.

00:10:55.080 --> 00:11:02.240
So we should have probably
not put up the answer there

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:02.915
and re-pole.

00:11:05.401 --> 00:11:05.900
Yes.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:09.700
So here, if we have
an electron that's

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:12.480
attracted to both
nuclei, then we

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:14.560
want to think about
whether that's

00:11:14.560 --> 00:11:16.950
going to be lower
or higher in energy

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:18.940
than something in
an atomic orbital.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:20.940
So if it's attracted
to both, it's

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.580
going to be more
stably bound to those,

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:27.600
It will be harder to remove
that electron, which means

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:31.030
that it's lower down in energy.

00:11:31.030 --> 00:11:34.450
And so we should look at
that, and we're going to.

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:40.530
So the answer is it should
be lower energy, more stable,

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:42.960
harder to remove that electron.

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:44.520
It's in a sweet spot.

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:47.890
It has two
positively-charged nuclei,

00:11:47.890 --> 00:11:50.140
and it's hanging out
right in the middle.

00:11:50.140 --> 00:11:51.310
It's very happy.

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:56.090
It's going to be more stable,
and that means lower in energy.

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:56.810
All right.

00:11:56.810 --> 00:11:59.040
So let's take a look at that.

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:01.910
So the electron is
lower in energy,

00:12:01.910 --> 00:12:04.480
and the bonding
orbital energy is also

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:08.660
going to be decreased compared
to the atomic orbitals,

00:12:08.660 --> 00:12:12.790
and that has to be true if
that's where the electron is.

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:15.030
So let's look at
the atomic orbital

00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:18.040
from a and the atomic
orbital from b.

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:23.310
And now, I'm going to put the
bonding orbital at a lower

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:24.850
energy level.

00:12:24.850 --> 00:12:26.920
First, I was going to
put the electrons on,

00:12:26.920 --> 00:12:31.380
and now, I'm going to put the
orbital at a lower energy.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:33.970
So remember, this is
increasing energy here,

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:37.000
so the atomic orbitals
would be up here,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.845
whereas the molecular
orbital is down here.

00:12:39.845 --> 00:12:44.220
The molecular bonding orbital
will be lower in energy.

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:47.150
And now we'll put
our electrons there.

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:50.800
So we have one electron
up here and one here,

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.720
and so when they
come together, we're

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:57.780
going to have two electrons
in this molecular orbital.

00:12:57.780 --> 00:12:59.930
So when you have
these two electrons

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:02.370
and they both occupy
the bonding orbital,

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:05.730
and this is the case
for H2, each H atom

00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:10.290
is bringing one electron,
H2 has these two electrons,

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:13.090
and that's going to
make H2 more stable.

00:13:13.090 --> 00:13:18.090
And we saw that before that
to associate the H2 bonds,

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:20.450
you have to add energy
into the system.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:26.070
H2 is more stable
than free H plus H.

00:13:26.070 --> 00:13:29.340
So when you bring
atomic orbitals together

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:32.890
and you have constructive
interference, an increased

00:13:32.890 --> 00:13:36.410
probability of electrons
between those two nuclei,

00:13:36.410 --> 00:13:38.200
that's a sweet spot.

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.970
Those electrons are going
to be very happy there,

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:45.200
and that will result in a more
stable, lower energy structure.

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:50.090
That's bonding.

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:55.394
But whenever there is a
positive event like this,

00:13:55.394 --> 00:13:57.310
there's always a negative
event because that's

00:13:57.310 --> 00:13:58.890
just how life works.

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:01.450
So we have bonding
orbitals, but we also

00:14:01.450 --> 00:14:06.350
have antibonding orbitals.

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:10.690
So antibonding arise from
the linear combination

00:14:10.690 --> 00:14:14.740
of atomic orbitals,
LCAO, through

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.430
destructive interference.

00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:22.960
So here these are going to
be destructively interfering,

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:27.140
and that will generate
a molecular orbital

00:14:27.140 --> 00:14:29.280
that is an antibonding orbital.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:31.820
So here are our
little nuclei again,

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:37.140
and this antibonding orbital
is called sigma 1s star.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:40.080
So we can write an
equation for this

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:46.300
as 1sa minus 1sb
equals sigma 1s star.

00:14:46.300 --> 00:14:50.440
That is an antibonding
molecular orbital.

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:53.900
And let's just think about
how this kind of shape

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:58.100
arises considering the
wavelike properties

00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:00.850
of these atomic orbitals.

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:04.440
So I'm going to now move
this equation up to the top.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:10.360
And now, I have my
1sa here, my 1sb here,

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:13.940
and now it's destructive
interference.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:17.710
So we have opposite phase
of the wave function.

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:22.340
And we'll put up a
wave function there.

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:26.790
Now, the next one has
the opposite phase,

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:29.940
so they're going to
destructively interfere.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.770
There is overlap
over here, but when

00:15:32.770 --> 00:15:35.430
you have destructive
interference,

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:39.420
then the amplitude
is going to decrease.

00:15:39.420 --> 00:15:43.600
So now, when we consider
this destructive interference

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:46.710
between these two
orbitals, you see that you

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:50.530
have what arises between them.

00:15:50.530 --> 00:15:54.480
Instead of enhanced probability
of finding an electron,

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:57.160
you actually get a node.

00:15:57.160 --> 00:16:01.220
So you have decreased
amplitude translates

00:16:01.220 --> 00:16:06.240
to decreased probability density
between these two nuclei-- one

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:09.580
here, one here-- and
that results in a node

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:11.500
between the two nuclei.

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.090
So in the antibonding
orbital, there

00:16:15.090 --> 00:16:17.640
is a much lower
probability that it

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:23.520
will be in this sweet spot
between the two nuclei

00:16:23.520 --> 00:16:25.860
that have this nice,
positive charge for it's

00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:28.220
little negative
charge, so there's

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:32.380
pretty much no shot at being
in that nice, sweet spot.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:34.790
And so what that
ends up meaning is

00:16:34.790 --> 00:16:37.770
that an electron and
an antibonding orbital

00:16:37.770 --> 00:16:42.410
is pretty much excluded
from that internuclear

00:16:42.410 --> 00:16:46.180
region, that region
between those two nuclei,

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:49.110
and that results in
a molecular orbital

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:52.310
that has higher energy
than the atomic orbital.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:55.650
There's just no chance of
being in that wonderful spot.

00:16:55.650 --> 00:16:58.610
It's really very sad
for the poor electron

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:02.140
that has to occupy an
antibonding orbital.

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:06.970
So now, let's put this
on our energy scale.

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:09.780
So we'll go back to
our energy scale.

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:13.940
And we saw before that
when we had 1sa and 1sb

00:17:13.940 --> 00:17:16.869
and you had a sigma
1s, a bonding orbital,

00:17:16.869 --> 00:17:19.020
that was lower in energy.

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:22.500
Electrons that occupy it
are more stable compared

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:26.329
to their positions in the
atomic orbital, but we also

00:17:26.329 --> 00:17:30.150
now have an antibonding orbital
from destructive interference

00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:33.720
between the wave functions
of the atomic orbitals,

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:35.900
and that's higher in energy.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:38.470
And so that's up here.

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:40.610
So this is what our
diagram is going

00:17:40.610 --> 00:17:44.190
to look like that brings
two atomic orbitals together

00:17:44.190 --> 00:17:48.430
to create two
molecular orbitals.

00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:51.670
So the antibonding
orbital up here

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:54.860
is raised in energy
by the same amount

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:58.660
that the bonding
energy is lowered.

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:02.900
And so that gives
rise to this diagram.

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:06.370
And importantly,
as I mentioned, we

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:10.070
have N atomic orbitals
forming N molecular orbitals.

00:18:10.070 --> 00:18:12.280
So if we have two
atomic orbitals,

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:15.290
we generate two
molecular orbitals,

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:20.250
one is bonding, lower in energy,
and one is antibonding, higher

00:18:20.250 --> 00:18:22.151
in energy.

00:18:22.151 --> 00:18:22.650
All right.

00:18:22.650 --> 00:18:24.500
So let's take a look
at some examples.

00:18:28.020 --> 00:18:33.390
So always start with hydrogen.
So hydrogen has how many

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:34.262
electrons?

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:39.160
One hydrogen, hydrogen atom.

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:39.966
AUDIENCE: One.

00:18:39.966 --> 00:18:41.140
CATHERINE DRENNAN: One.

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:44.080
So we have two hydrogen
atoms, and so we

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:48.430
have two 1s orbitals, 1sa, 1sb.

00:18:48.430 --> 00:18:53.840
And now where do we want
to put our electrons?

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:56.160
In the highest energy
possible, lower energy?

00:18:56.160 --> 00:18:57.370
Where do we want to put them?

00:18:57.370 --> 00:18:58.240
AUDIENCE: Lower.

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:00.980
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Always
start with lower energy.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:04.190
So we're going to
put them down here.

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:10.220
And so this is now
the MO diagram for H2.

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:13.180
And we can write the
electron configuration

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:16.870
for the MO diagram, which you'll
note is a different electron

00:19:16.870 --> 00:19:19.260
configuration than you were
writing when you were looking

00:19:19.260 --> 00:19:22.170
at the periodic table because
now we're not writing it

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:25.830
in terms of 1s 2, 2s
2, we're writing it

00:19:25.830 --> 00:19:28.750
in terms of molecular orbitals.

00:19:28.750 --> 00:19:30.990
And there are some of
these on the problem set,

00:19:30.990 --> 00:19:33.440
and I tried to indicate
example to make

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:36.300
sure you know what kind
of electron configurations

00:19:36.300 --> 00:19:37.420
we're talking about.

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:40.860
So for MO diagrams, when it
says electron configuration

00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:44.720
we're talking about where the
electrons are with respect

00:19:44.720 --> 00:19:46.470
to the molecular orbitals.

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:49.910
So the answer to this
would be sigma 1s 2.

00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:54.120
There are two electrons in the
molecular orbital, sigma 1s.

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:58.630
Good.

00:19:58.630 --> 00:20:05.704
So that means that you can do
the same thing for dihelium,

00:20:05.704 --> 00:20:06.953
and that's a clicker question.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:29.110
So let's just take
10 more seconds.

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:46.050
OK, you can vote.

00:20:46.050 --> 00:20:46.555
All right.

00:20:49.640 --> 00:21:03.090
So does someone want to
tell me-- that is correct--

00:21:03.090 --> 00:21:07.034
what's number two for?

00:21:07.034 --> 00:21:13.702
For hydrogen. What about number
three, what was wrong there?

00:21:13.702 --> 00:21:15.074
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:15.074 --> 00:21:17.240
CATHERINE DRENNAN: OK,
everyone's doing really well.

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:17.740
Yeah.

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:24.650
So all of the electrons
were parallel in there,

00:21:24.650 --> 00:21:26.730
and what does that violate?

00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:28.676
What would be true in that case?

00:21:28.676 --> 00:21:30.120
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:31.120
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Yeah.

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:36.650
And so they'd have the same
four principle quantum numbers.

00:21:36.650 --> 00:21:38.120
This is not allowed.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:39.600
So that one's not good.

00:21:39.600 --> 00:21:41.212
And what's wrong with four?

00:21:41.212 --> 00:21:42.821
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:42.821 --> 00:21:44.820
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Yeah,
star was on the bottom.

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:46.100
So they were flipped around.

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:48.770
Antibonding was lower in energy.

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:50.810
Great.

00:21:50.810 --> 00:21:53.950
So we'll just put
those in over here,

00:21:53.950 --> 00:21:57.450
and so we had two electrons.

00:21:57.450 --> 00:21:59.050
Helium brings two.

00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:02.300
So two went into
the bonding, and two

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:07.030
went into the antibonding
with opposite spins.

00:22:07.030 --> 00:22:09.330
And we have the
bonding, lower energy;

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:11.191
antibonding, higher energy.

00:22:11.191 --> 00:22:11.690
All right.

00:22:11.690 --> 00:22:16.980
So then we can put in the
electron configuration here,

00:22:16.980 --> 00:22:23.600
and we have sigma 1s
2, sigma 1s star 2,

00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:27.250
so that's the electron
configuration.

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:30.750
Now interestingly,
you see, you have two

00:22:30.750 --> 00:22:33.790
at lower energy and
two at higher energy,

00:22:33.790 --> 00:22:38.630
so there's no net loss
or gain in energy of H2

00:22:38.630 --> 00:22:42.080
compared to just
two helium atoms.

00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:48.190
And so that raises the
question, does helium 2 exist?

00:22:48.190 --> 00:22:51.210
So what would molecular
orbital theory

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:54.900
tell you about whether it
exists, and it would actually

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:57.650
predict that it does not exist.

00:22:57.650 --> 00:23:00.710
And the way that molecular
orbital theory gives you

00:23:00.710 --> 00:23:03.970
these predictions is through
the calculation of something

00:23:03.970 --> 00:23:05.910
called bond order.

00:23:05.910 --> 00:23:09.300
So bond order is
half of the number

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:13.510
of bonding electrons minus
the number of antibonding

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:14.690
electrons.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:19.730
So let's just write out what the
bond order for helium would be.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:28.800
So helium 2, our
dihelium molecule.

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:34.670
So we have a bond
order equals 1/2.

00:23:34.670 --> 00:23:36.280
There's always 1/2.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:38.820
And now, the number of
bonding electrons, so

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:41.060
how many bonding electrons
do we have for helium?

00:23:41.060 --> 00:23:42.066
AUDIENCE: Two.

00:23:42.066 --> 00:23:44.010
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Two.

00:23:44.010 --> 00:23:47.555
How many antibonding electrons
do we have for dihelium?

00:23:47.555 --> 00:23:48.355
AUDIENCE: Two

00:23:48.355 --> 00:23:50.280
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Two.

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:53.005
And can someone do
this math for me?

00:23:53.005 --> 00:23:53.761
AUDIENCE: Zero.

00:23:53.761 --> 00:23:54.760
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Zero.

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:55.550
Right.

00:23:55.550 --> 00:23:57.770
So that would
suggest a bond order

00:23:57.770 --> 00:24:02.970
of 0, which means no bond.

00:24:02.970 --> 00:24:08.430
And let's just compare
that to hydrogen, H2,

00:24:08.430 --> 00:24:13.080
which should have a
bond order equal to 1/2.

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:14.620
It's always a 1/2.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:18.634
In the hydrogen, how many
bonding electrons did we have?

00:24:18.634 --> 00:24:19.238
AUDIENCE: Two.

00:24:19.238 --> 00:24:20.488
CATHERINE DRENNAN: We had two.

00:24:20.488 --> 00:24:23.030
How many antibonding
electrons did we have?

00:24:23.030 --> 00:24:23.750
AUDIENCE: Zero.

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:24.770
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Zero.

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:26.120
And the math?

00:24:26.120 --> 00:24:26.995
Bond order is?

00:24:26.995 --> 00:24:27.505
AUDIENCE: 1.

00:24:27.505 --> 00:24:29.280
CATHERINE DRENNAN: 1.

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:33.450
So that means 1 bond
or a single bond.

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:42.920
So MO theory would predict that
dihelium, has no bond, i.e.

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:45.690
it's not really a
molecule without a bond,

00:24:45.690 --> 00:24:47.450
but H2 should exist.

00:24:52.200 --> 00:24:55.810
So let's take a look at
what experiment tells us,

00:24:55.810 --> 00:25:02.340
and it does exist, but
only really not that much.

00:25:02.340 --> 00:25:08.360
So it was not discovered until
1993, which for some of you

00:25:08.360 --> 00:25:10.570
might seem like quite
a long time ago,

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:12.200
but since we've
been mostly talking

00:25:12.200 --> 00:25:16.120
about discoveries that
were made in the 1800s,

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:18.100
it took a long time
before someone could

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:21.030
prove that dihelium existed.

00:25:21.030 --> 00:25:25.460
And if we look at the bond
association energy for H2,

00:25:25.460 --> 00:25:32.502
0.01, and compare
that to H2, 432,

00:25:32.502 --> 00:25:34.840
dihelium really doesn't
exist very much.

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:40.670
0 is a much better approximation
of its bond than 1 would be.

00:25:40.670 --> 00:25:43.390
It really is not a
very good molecule.

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:47.420
So I would call this a win
for molecular orbital theory.

00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:53.326
It correctly predicts
that our helium 2 is not

00:25:53.326 --> 00:25:54.700
going to be a very
good molecule,

00:25:54.700 --> 00:26:00.220
but H2 will be a good
molecule, and that works.

00:26:00.220 --> 00:26:01.015
All right.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:06.860
Now, let's consider 2s.

00:26:06.860 --> 00:26:10.740
So 2s orbitals are
analogous to 1s

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:15.090
except that you have to
remember that they're bigger.

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:19.200
So we have our 1s and our 2s,
but for the purposes of this,

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:22.070
it doesn't really matter.

00:26:22.070 --> 00:26:28.190
So let's look at a diagram
now that has 1s and 2s.

00:26:28.190 --> 00:26:30.870
So we have lithium.

00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:34.640
So how many electrons
does lithium have?

00:26:34.640 --> 00:26:35.500
AUDIENCE: Three.

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:36.820
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Yep.

00:26:36.820 --> 00:26:39.410
So we'll put on
lithium, dilithium.

00:26:39.410 --> 00:26:44.840
We'll put on lithiums has
two in 1s and one in 2s,

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:50.110
and so we have one lithium
here and one lithium over here.

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:53.600
And our 1s orbitals are
going to be lower energy,

00:26:53.600 --> 00:26:54.930
so they're down here.

00:26:54.930 --> 00:26:57.770
Our 2s orbitals are
higher in energy.

00:26:57.770 --> 00:27:01.830
So that goes for both the atomic
and the molecular orbitals

00:27:01.830 --> 00:27:03.400
that are generated.

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:09.280
So bringing together 1s with
1s, we get sigma 1s and also

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:11.290
sigma star 1s.

00:27:11.290 --> 00:27:14.180
And so we can start
putting our electrons in.

00:27:14.180 --> 00:27:17.210
We're going to start with the
lowest energy and move on up.

00:27:17.210 --> 00:27:20.470
So we have four electrons
that we need to put in,

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:23.040
so we fill up everything here.

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:25.720
And now we go up to our 2s.

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:30.510
The 2s orbitals will generate
signal 2s and sigma 2s star.

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:36.020
We have two electrons, so
they both can go down here.

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:40.230
So here is what our
MO diagram looks like.

00:27:40.230 --> 00:27:43.500
We can write out the
electron configuration again,

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:45.840
based on this diagram.

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:50.970
So we have two electrons in
sigma 1s, so we have a 2 there.

00:27:50.970 --> 00:27:54.460
We have two electrons in
sigma 1s star, our antibonding

00:27:54.460 --> 00:27:59.540
orbital, and we have two
electrons in sigma 2s.

00:27:59.540 --> 00:28:03.420
And now we can calculate
the bond order, which

00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:04.847
is another clicker question.

00:28:22.050 --> 00:28:23.490
OK, just 10 more seconds.

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:39.760
Excellent.

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:41.780
84%.

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:48.320
So if we do out the math
here, we always have our 1/2.

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:51.510
We have four bonding electrons.

00:28:51.510 --> 00:28:53.990
We have two down
here and two up here.

00:28:53.990 --> 00:28:58.450
We have two antibonding
electrons in our sigma 1s star,

00:28:58.450 --> 00:29:01.250
and so that gives us
a bond order of 1.

00:29:01.250 --> 00:29:03.790
And in fact, the
dissociation energy

00:29:03.790 --> 00:29:05.410
does suggest there is a bond.

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:07.350
It's not a great bond.

00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:12.860
It's 105 kilojoules per mole,
not necessarily enough to power

00:29:12.860 --> 00:29:18.290
a starship, but still
this molecule does exist.

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:21.040
All right.

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:25.690
So let's look at beryllium
now, do another example.

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:31.180
So how many electrons is
beryllium going to have?

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:33.230
It will have four.

00:29:33.230 --> 00:29:35.300
So we'll put those up.

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:39.670
Now, we're going to start with
our lowest energy orbital,

00:29:39.670 --> 00:29:43.020
and we're going to put some
in the antibonding as well.

00:29:43.020 --> 00:29:46.740
And then we'll do this,
and then we'll do that.

00:29:46.740 --> 00:29:49.520
And we filled up everything.

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:52.460
And so we can write
out our configuration.

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:57.050
We have two in our
sigma 1s orbital.

00:29:57.050 --> 00:30:00.140
We have two in
our sigma 1s star.

00:30:00.140 --> 00:30:05.430
We have two in our sigma 2s,
and two in our sigma 2s star

00:30:05.430 --> 00:30:07.060
antibonding orbital there.

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:12.130
And now there are
two different ways

00:30:12.130 --> 00:30:14.850
that I can calculate
the bond order here,

00:30:14.850 --> 00:30:17.470
and we'll do both of them and
show you that they come out

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:19.230
the same way.

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:21.430
One way that we
can calculate this

00:30:21.430 --> 00:30:25.580
is to consider all electrons.

00:30:25.580 --> 00:30:29.190
So if we consider all
electrons, our bond order,

00:30:29.190 --> 00:30:36.380
and that's often just said
B.O., is 1/2 of our bonding.

00:30:36.380 --> 00:30:40.690
And now we can count up
both the 1s and the 2s.

00:30:40.690 --> 00:30:43.430
So how many bonding
electrons do we have?

00:30:46.070 --> 00:30:53.920
We should have four, so we have
two here, two here, so four.

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:56.430
How many antibonding?

00:30:56.430 --> 00:31:03.370
Also four, so that
suggest a bond order of 0.

00:31:03.370 --> 00:31:08.170
Or we could just consider
our valence electrons,

00:31:08.170 --> 00:31:11.630
so that would be
the electrons in 2s,

00:31:11.630 --> 00:31:15.550
and if we do that,
bond order equals 1/2.

00:31:15.550 --> 00:31:18.930
It's always a 1/2, so how
many valence electrons

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:21.490
do we have in bonding orbitals?

00:31:21.490 --> 00:31:22.370
Two.

00:31:22.370 --> 00:31:24.980
How many in
antibonding orbitals?

00:31:24.980 --> 00:31:26.620
Two.

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:28.530
And that gives the answer of 0.

00:31:28.530 --> 00:31:32.860
So it should always work unless
you do something very strange.

00:31:32.860 --> 00:31:37.250
You should be able to do it both
ways and get the same answer.

00:31:37.250 --> 00:31:39.290
So if this is a
complicated problem,

00:31:39.290 --> 00:31:42.200
you might want to only
consider the valence electrons.

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:44.230
In fact, on a test,
you may only be

00:31:44.230 --> 00:31:47.090
asked to draw the
molecular orbital diagrams

00:31:47.090 --> 00:31:49.020
for the valence
electrons, and you don't

00:31:49.020 --> 00:31:53.740
have to do the other ones.

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:56.010
So that should work both ways.

00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:59.940
And we get a bond order
of 0, and in fact,

00:31:59.940 --> 00:32:03.980
the dissociation energy is
only 9 kilojoules per mole.

00:32:03.980 --> 00:32:07.020
It's a little stronger
than dihelium,

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:09.970
but this is an
exceedingly weak molecule.

00:32:09.970 --> 00:32:13.310
So when you have the same
number of electrons and bonding

00:32:13.310 --> 00:32:18.186
as antibonding, it doesn't
lead to a very strong molecule.

00:32:18.186 --> 00:32:20.400
All right.

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:22.610
That's the orbitals.

00:32:22.610 --> 00:32:27.150
Now, it's time for molecules
that have p orbitals as well.

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:37.610
So in this case, now I have my
p orbital and another p orbital.

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:42.064
And we have our
nuclei in the middle,

00:32:42.064 --> 00:32:43.730
and we're going to
bring these together,

00:32:43.730 --> 00:32:47.370
and we will have
constructive interference.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:50.940
And so here we're
bringing together

00:32:50.940 --> 00:33:00.740
2p x of a and 2p xb
or 2p ya and 2p yb.

00:33:00.740 --> 00:33:04.660
So just x and y we're
considering right now.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:11.100
And if we bring those together
with constructive interference,

00:33:11.100 --> 00:33:14.150
then we're going to form
a bonding orbital that

00:33:14.150 --> 00:33:19.390
has enhanced probability
density in both cases

00:33:19.390 --> 00:33:22.920
and nodal plane
along the bond axis

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:27.100
because we had nodal planes
along there to begin with.

00:33:27.100 --> 00:33:31.540
So if we think about this
and we have both of these,

00:33:31.540 --> 00:33:34.660
we're bringing them
together and they're

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:37.270
going to interfere
constructively, enhance

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:40.720
probability density here,
enhance probability density

00:33:40.720 --> 00:33:44.750
down here, but we still have
our nodal plane because we

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:46.510
started out with one.

00:33:46.510 --> 00:33:52.440
And so if we have a nodal plane,
this cannot be a sigma orbital.

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:56.630
It has to be a pi orbital,
because sigma orbitals are not

00:33:56.630 --> 00:34:01.340
going to have a nodal plane
along the bonding access.

00:34:01.340 --> 00:34:01.840
All right.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:09.699
So we could generate pi
2px or pi 2py this way.

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:12.429
So a pi orbital is
a molecular orbital

00:34:12.429 --> 00:34:15.900
that has a nodal plane through
the bond axis or maybe I

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:19.429
should say along the bond axis,
so here is our nodal plane

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:21.263
right through the bond axis.

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:30.909
We can also have
antibonding, which

00:34:30.909 --> 00:34:33.690
means destructive interference.

00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:35.650
So now, I'm going
to be subtracting

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:38.760
one of these from
one of these, and I'm

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:42.130
going to get something
that looks like this,

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:51.780
and it will be pi 2px
star or pi 2py star,

00:34:51.780 --> 00:34:56.179
and it will have
two nodal planes.

00:34:56.179 --> 00:34:57.355
So let's look at this.

00:34:57.355 --> 00:34:59.430
So this is destructive
interference.

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:01.780
I'm subtracting one of
these from one of these,

00:35:01.780 --> 00:35:03.910
so the phase has to change.

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:06.230
So I'm going to change
the phase on one of them

00:35:06.230 --> 00:35:08.060
and then bring them together.

00:35:08.060 --> 00:35:11.760
Now, we're not going to have
that awesome, constructive

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:15.760
interference increased
probability density.

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:18.820
These are negatively
interacting with each other.

00:35:18.820 --> 00:35:23.510
And this generates a nodal
plane between the molecules.

00:35:23.510 --> 00:35:25.990
They really look much
more like this now,

00:35:25.990 --> 00:35:29.400
so we have still our nodal
plane through the bond.

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:30.390
We had that before.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:31.780
We're always going to have that.

00:35:31.780 --> 00:35:36.780
But now we have an additional
nodal plane between the nuclei.

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:40.950
So in one case, we have enhanced
density, probability density

00:35:40.950 --> 00:35:41.450
again.

00:35:41.450 --> 00:35:43.950
And the other case,
in antibonding,

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:47.600
we have another nodal plane.

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:48.160
All right.

00:35:48.160 --> 00:35:49.660
So now, let's look
at what happens

00:35:49.660 --> 00:35:55.170
to the energies of
these pi orbitals.

00:35:55.170 --> 00:35:58.360
And the diagrams that
I'm about to show you,

00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:01.750
we're only talking
about px and py now.

00:36:01.750 --> 00:36:05.320
We have for the
moment forgotten 2pz.

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:08.850
So these diagrams are
rated I for incomplete.

00:36:08.850 --> 00:36:11.140
Warning to the viewer,
people come to me

00:36:11.140 --> 00:36:13.790
and go where are the 2pz?

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:16.740
Yes, they're not
in these diagrams,

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:19.450
but when you're asked
for a complete diagram,

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:22.085
you will always have to
put those orbitals in.

00:36:22.085 --> 00:36:24.600
And in fact, completing
these diagrams

00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:27.220
could be a question
you get later.

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:30.710
But for now, we're
going to have 2pz here,

00:36:30.710 --> 00:36:34.880
but it's not forming a molecular
orbital in this diagram.

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:37.170
This diagram is,
thus, incomplete,

00:36:37.170 --> 00:36:40.980
but we're going to start simple
and build more complicated.

00:36:40.980 --> 00:36:45.280
So only 2p orbitals first, and
then we'll add the third one.

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:49.230
Because this compound doesn't
actually need that orbital,

00:36:49.230 --> 00:36:51.450
so we're good for now.

00:36:51.450 --> 00:36:51.950
All right.

00:36:51.950 --> 00:36:55.680
So we have moved on to
the first element that has

00:36:55.680 --> 00:36:59.000
a p electron in a p orbital.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.280
We have boron, and
we have two of them.

00:37:02.280 --> 00:37:08.430
So now I dropped off
1s to simplify this.

00:37:08.430 --> 00:37:10.990
Now, we just have our
valence electrons,

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:13.900
so it's a good thing we can
calculate bond order just using

00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:15.360
our valence electrons.

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:15.860
All right.

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:21.390
So we have two in 2s
and one in 2px or 2py.

00:37:21.390 --> 00:37:24.210
I could have put
it in either place.

00:37:24.210 --> 00:37:26.690
So let's put in
where they would go.

00:37:26.690 --> 00:37:29.250
So we have 2s orbitals.

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:34.120
They'll go into bonding
sigma 2s first, then

00:37:34.120 --> 00:37:43.400
into antibonding, sigma 2s star,
and now we have p electrons,

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:47.490
and we're going to put
them into our pi orbitals,

00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:48.960
our molecular orbitals.

00:37:48.960 --> 00:37:52.170
I'll put one in, and where am
I going to put the other one?

00:37:52.170 --> 00:37:54.235
Am I going to put it
next to it or over here?

00:37:54.235 --> 00:37:55.370
What do you think?

00:37:55.370 --> 00:37:56.600
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:57.840
CATHERINE DRENNAN: Yeah.

00:37:57.840 --> 00:38:00.820
So we're going to do that
because, again, when you're

00:38:00.820 --> 00:38:03.890
going to sit on a bus, you want
to have if they're degenerate

00:38:03.890 --> 00:38:06.340
in energy levels
as they are here,

00:38:06.340 --> 00:38:10.070
you're always going to put
one electron in each orbital

00:38:10.070 --> 00:38:13.190
of the same energy first
before you pair them up,

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.970
and they'll have parallel spins.

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:18.140
So we're reviewing
things we learned before.

00:38:18.140 --> 00:38:20.720
I love doing that.

00:38:20.720 --> 00:38:25.210
So now, let's see what our
electron configuration is,

00:38:25.210 --> 00:38:29.260
and this is just the valence
electron configuration.

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:30.130
We're simplifying.

00:38:30.130 --> 00:38:33.730
We're not going to
consider the 1s orbital,

00:38:33.730 --> 00:38:35.000
and we can write this down.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.660
So we have two
electrons in sigma 2s,

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:42.880
and we have two electrons in
sigma 2s star, our antibonding

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:50.250
orbital, and we have one in
pi 2px and one in pi 2py.

00:38:50.250 --> 00:38:52.940
And I can put a
1 or not put a 1.

00:38:52.940 --> 00:38:57.890
If I don't put anything,
for a 1, 1 is assumed.

00:38:57.890 --> 00:39:02.080
And we can calculate
our bond order as well.

00:39:02.080 --> 00:39:04.380
So we have 1/2, and
again, we're just

00:39:04.380 --> 00:39:07.170
using our valence
electrons, but that's OK.

00:39:07.170 --> 00:39:11.580
We have four now who are
bonding, two down here, two

00:39:11.580 --> 00:39:13.960
up here, these are
bonding orbitals,

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:16.580
and we have two that
are antibonding.

00:39:16.580 --> 00:39:18.960
And notice for our
pi orbitals, this

00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:22.200
is what we saw before
bonding are lower in energy,

00:39:22.200 --> 00:39:24.500
antibonding are
higher in energy.

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:27.810
With the bonding orbitals, we
had constructive interference,

00:39:27.810 --> 00:39:31.590
enhanced probability of the
electrons near the nuclei,

00:39:31.590 --> 00:39:33.650
and so that's lower in energy.

00:39:33.650 --> 00:39:36.710
But in our antibonding
ones, we have a nodal plane

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:38.230
in between our nuclei.

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:40.860
So we don't have any
probability that electrons

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:43.740
are right in between there
because there's a nodal plane,

00:39:43.740 --> 00:39:46.600
so those are higher in energy.

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:50.670
So here is our B2 diagram.

00:39:50.670 --> 00:39:55.410
So now let's try the same
thing for carbon, C2,

00:39:55.410 --> 00:39:57.000
and that is a clicker question.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:23.040
All right.

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:25.756
Let's just take 10 more seconds.

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:44.270
So let's take a look
at that over here.

00:40:44.270 --> 00:40:47.490
The easiest thing to do
to answer this question

00:40:47.490 --> 00:40:50.600
was to fill in the
diagram in your handout.

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:55.910
And so if you did that, you
would have put two down here

00:40:55.910 --> 00:40:58.760
and you would have
put two up here.

00:40:58.760 --> 00:41:04.070
Then you would have put
one here, one there,

00:41:04.070 --> 00:41:06.880
another one there,
and another one there.

00:41:09.460 --> 00:41:15.710
So now we have used these
up, and so our configuration

00:41:15.710 --> 00:41:27.270
is sigma 2s 2, sigma star
2, pi 2px 2, pi 2py 2.

00:41:27.270 --> 00:41:30.270
And the bond order is 1/2.

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:35.540
There are six bonding
electrons-- 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6--

00:41:35.540 --> 00:41:40.790
and two antibonding
electrons, and so that adds up

00:41:40.790 --> 00:41:44.660
to a bond order of 2.

00:41:44.660 --> 00:41:46.750
And so sometimes
on a test, they'll

00:41:46.750 --> 00:41:49.760
be a simple question what is
the bond order, but to get there

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:53.260
you have to draw your whole
molecular orbital diagram

00:41:53.260 --> 00:41:56.430
and figure out how many bonding
and how many antibonding,

00:41:56.430 --> 00:41:59.507
so these are not really
that fast questions.

00:41:59.507 --> 00:42:00.090
And it's nice.

00:42:00.090 --> 00:42:01.839
Sometimes we give you
like a little space,

00:42:01.839 --> 00:42:04.800
and you see this whole little
molecular orbital diagram

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:07.590
fit in there to
answer the question.

00:42:07.590 --> 00:42:08.090
All right.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:11.450
So let's just compare these
two diagrams for a minute.

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:18.470
So in both cases, we had 2s
orbitals, two atomic orbitals

00:42:18.470 --> 00:42:23.610
for 2s, and they both generated
two molecular orbitals,

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:26.050
a bonding and an antibonding.

00:42:26.050 --> 00:42:28.810
The bonding is lower in
energy, and the antibonding

00:42:28.810 --> 00:42:30.520
is higher in energy.

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:34.590
We also had two 2px
atomic orbitals.

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:41.320
They generated 2
pi 2 px orbitals,

00:42:41.320 --> 00:42:44.450
one bonding, one antibonding.

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:49.130
And the same for our two
atomic orbitals for 2 py.

00:42:49.130 --> 00:42:53.270
We had two of those, and they
generated one lower energy

00:42:53.270 --> 00:42:58.500
bonding, pi, bonding and
one pi star antibonding.

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:02.220
So you always have N
atomic orbitals generating

00:43:02.220 --> 00:43:06.390
N molecular orbitals.

00:43:06.390 --> 00:43:09.150
So the stability of
the resulting molecules

00:43:09.150 --> 00:43:12.440
in these cases depend on
how many of the electrons

00:43:12.440 --> 00:43:15.540
are bonding, how many
are in energy lower

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:18.070
as a result of formation
of the molecule,

00:43:18.070 --> 00:43:22.370
and how many are at higher
energy as a result of formation

00:43:22.370 --> 00:43:23.570
of the molecule.

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:27.410
And if the net result are more
electrons in lower energy, more

00:43:27.410 --> 00:43:30.620
electrons in bonding
orbitals, then that molecule

00:43:30.620 --> 00:43:31.820
is more stable.

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:34.920
If there's a very
slight or no difference,

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:37.600
then that's not a
very stable molecule.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:39.820
So now let's just
compare these two

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:44.640
and think about which of these
is going to be more stable.

00:43:44.640 --> 00:43:48.000
So we have our
configurations again.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.020
So in the case of B2,
how many electrons

00:43:52.020 --> 00:43:54.470
are in lower energy
or bonding orbitals?

00:43:54.470 --> 00:43:55.745
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:55.745 --> 00:43:58.590
