00:46:43.250 --> 00:46:45.190
Let's quiet down a minute.

00:46:45.190 --> 00:46:47.610
You can hear the answer.

00:46:47.610 --> 00:46:50.240
So this one is true.

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:52.300
The second one is not true.

00:46:52.300 --> 00:46:55.140
A bond order of zero
doesn't mean that you just

00:46:55.140 --> 00:46:56.810
have antibonding orbitals.

00:46:56.810 --> 00:46:59.640
Whenever you bring together
two atomic orbitals,

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:02.190
you have to make two
molecular orbitals.

00:47:02.190 --> 00:47:04.990
So it isn't that sometimes
you make bonding orbitals

00:47:04.990 --> 00:47:07.360
and sometimes you make
antibonding orbitals.

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:10.140
Every time you bring
together two atomic orbitals,

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:14.346
you make two molecular orbitals,
one that's lower in energy,

00:47:14.346 --> 00:47:15.970
and that's the bonding
orbital, and one

00:47:15.970 --> 00:47:20.300
that's higher in energy, and
that's the antibonding orbital.

00:47:20.300 --> 00:47:21.790
So that is not what that means.

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:23.590
A bond order of
zero means that you

00:47:23.590 --> 00:47:27.260
have equal numbers of electrons
in your bonding and antibonding

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:28.360
orbitals.

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:32.400
So there's no net stabilization
due to the formation

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:35.210
of these bonds.

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:38.340
So here bonding occurs
when you bring together

00:47:38.340 --> 00:47:41.690
two atomic orbitals to make
two molecular orbitals that

00:47:41.690 --> 00:47:43.120
are both of lower energy.

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:43.720
No.

00:47:43.720 --> 00:47:47.630
Every time you make the two
orbitals, one is lower energy,

00:47:47.630 --> 00:47:48.790
one is higher that energy.

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:51.370
You can't make two that
are both lower in energy.

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:54.000
And bond order of 1 means
constructive interference

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:58.370
is generated at one
bonding orbital.

00:47:58.370 --> 00:48:00.460
That's not what a
bond order of 1 is.

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:02.740
And again, every time you
generate a bonding orbital,

00:48:02.740 --> 00:48:04.780
you generate an
antibonding orbital.

00:48:04.780 --> 00:48:10.360
And 1 means that you have
twice as many electrons

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:12.790
in your bonding orbitals
as antibonding orbitals

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:15.700
because the formula is
1/2 the number of bonding

00:48:15.700 --> 00:48:17.620
minus antibonding.

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:20.360
But that's good, and it's
important to remember

00:48:20.360 --> 00:48:25.640
that sigma orbitals are
symmetric around the bond axis.

00:48:25.640 --> 00:48:26.140
All right.

00:48:26.140 --> 00:48:29.830
So we had these diagrams
for boron and carbon,

00:48:29.830 --> 00:48:37.400
just talking about the
interactions of the px and py,

00:48:37.400 --> 00:48:40.350
and so we had
forgotten about our pz.

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:41.810
And you can't do that on a test.

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:44.350
You get into trouble,
so I'm always

00:48:44.350 --> 00:48:47.240
telling people for
these two handouts,

00:48:47.240 --> 00:48:49.360
you must include the
molecular orbitals that

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:51.640
are derived from p to z.

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:54.120
So on a test, you need to put
them even if they're empty.

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:56.160
Even if they don't
have anything in them,

00:48:56.160 --> 00:48:58.659
they need to be part of your
molecular orbital diagram.

00:48:58.659 --> 00:49:00.075
We didn't have
them in the diagram

00:49:00.075 --> 00:49:01.900
because we hadn't
talked about them yet,

00:49:01.900 --> 00:49:04.100
so now we're going
to talk about them.

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:09.690
So two pz orbitals, again,
this is on Monday's handout.

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:14.270
You have this linear
combination of atomic orbitals.

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:15.850
And all are p orbitals.

00:49:15.850 --> 00:49:17.760
They all look the
same as each other,

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:19.470
they're just different
in orientation.

00:49:19.470 --> 00:49:22.860
You have one along x,
one along y, one along z,

00:49:22.860 --> 00:49:24.200
but they're the same.

00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:30.150
So now we're going to bring
our two pz orbitals together,

00:49:30.150 --> 00:49:32.320
and we're going to do it
along the bonding axis.

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:35.790
So we've defined this as the
bonding axis in the class,

00:49:35.790 --> 00:49:38.620
so we'll bring them
together, and they'll

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:42.675
be constructive interference
with our bonding orbitals.

00:49:42.675 --> 00:49:44.550
There's always constructive
interference that

00:49:44.550 --> 00:49:46.650
generates bonding orbitals.

00:49:46.650 --> 00:49:53.730
And so we're going to create a
enhanced amplitude as the wave

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:55.730
functions come
together, and it's

00:49:55.730 --> 00:49:59.120
going to be
cylindrically symmetric.

00:49:59.120 --> 00:50:02.190
So what type of orbital do
you think this is going to be,

00:50:02.190 --> 00:50:03.175
sigma or pi?

00:50:03.175 --> 00:50:04.030
AUDIENCE: Sigma.

00:50:04.030 --> 00:50:06.530
CATHERINE DRENNAN:
It'll be sigma

00:50:06.530 --> 00:50:09.380
because it's
cylindrically symmetric.

00:50:09.380 --> 00:50:14.440
So we do not have any bonding
plane along the bond axis,

00:50:14.440 --> 00:50:16.730
and it's symmetric around.

00:50:16.730 --> 00:50:20.530
And we have enhanced
probability density,

00:50:20.530 --> 00:50:23.590
and we have the wave
function squared

00:50:23.590 --> 00:50:26.590
enhanced probability of having
an electron between the two

00:50:26.590 --> 00:50:27.700
nuclei.

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:31.730
And so this is a sigma 2pz.

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:37.100
So p orbitals can form
sigma molecular orbitals.

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:41.120
So we do have nodes
passing through our nuclei.

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:42.680
Here are our nuclei again.

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:43.520
We do have them.

00:50:43.520 --> 00:50:45.900
They were here before
in our p orbitals.

00:50:45.900 --> 00:50:51.240
There's the nodal plane in our
p orbitals, but we do not have,

00:50:51.240 --> 00:50:56.220
in this case, a node
along the bond axis.

00:50:56.220 --> 00:50:58.910
So that is our bonding.

00:50:58.910 --> 00:51:02.720
So whenever you generate
a bonding orbital, which

00:51:02.720 --> 00:51:06.520
is going to be
lower energy, we're

00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:09.780
going to have our increased
amplitude between the nuclei,

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:13.430
again, our increased probability
density and therefore,

00:51:13.430 --> 00:51:15.100
lower energy.

00:51:15.100 --> 00:51:17.310
So whenever you have
constructive interference

00:51:17.310 --> 00:51:21.180
generating a molecular
orbital of lower energy,

00:51:21.180 --> 00:51:23.260
you got to create
something of higher energy.

00:51:23.260 --> 00:51:25.140
That's just how life works.

00:51:25.140 --> 00:51:28.520
So we also are going
to have antibonding

00:51:28.520 --> 00:51:31.814
orbitals, which are generated
by destructive interference.

00:51:31.814 --> 00:51:33.480
And again, these
orbitals can be thought

00:51:33.480 --> 00:51:35.890
about as wave functions,
and a property of waves

00:51:35.890 --> 00:51:39.370
is that they constructively
interfere and destructively

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:40.330
interfere.

00:51:40.330 --> 00:51:45.040
So now we can subtract
our two orbitals,

00:51:45.040 --> 00:51:48.010
which we're going
to switch the sign

00:51:48.010 --> 00:51:50.410
and they're going
to be out of phase.

00:51:50.410 --> 00:51:53.780
So they'll
destructively interfere,

00:51:53.780 --> 00:51:56.560
and that's going
to look like this.

00:51:56.560 --> 00:52:00.460
So now, you're going to generate
a nodal plane between the two

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:04.890
nuclei, but it's still
symmetric around the bond axis.

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:12.270
So this is a sigma 2pz star,
so it's an antibonding orbital.

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:14.960
So again, it's
sigma, so it's still

00:52:14.960 --> 00:52:19.750
cylindrically symmetrical with
no nodal plane along that bond

00:52:19.750 --> 00:52:25.210
axis, but you do have a new
nodal plane that's generated.

00:52:25.210 --> 00:52:28.400
So nodes pass, again,
through the nuclei,

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:31.970
but also now between
these two orbitals.

00:52:31.970 --> 00:52:33.600
So we have a new
nodal plane that's

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:37.490
generated that's
between these nuclei,

00:52:37.490 --> 00:52:41.160
and that's a result of
destructive interference.

00:52:41.160 --> 00:52:42.980
Generates that nodal plane.

00:52:42.980 --> 00:52:46.310
You have decreased
probability density

00:52:46.310 --> 00:52:50.040
for an electron
being found there.

00:52:50.040 --> 00:52:53.880
And so that poor electron is
shut out of that sweet spot.

00:52:53.880 --> 00:52:56.800
The electrons like to be
between those two nuclei

00:52:56.800 --> 00:53:00.800
where they have the two positive
charges of the nuclei and then

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:03.600
their little negative charge,
and they can sit right there

00:53:03.600 --> 00:53:06.530
and be very happy in
a low-energy state.

00:53:06.530 --> 00:53:09.940
But here there's really
lower probability density,

00:53:09.940 --> 00:53:12.840
lower likelihood the
electron will be found here,

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:14.730
and that generates
a molecular orbital

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:18.370
that's antibonding
or higher in energy.

00:53:18.370 --> 00:53:18.870
All right.

00:53:18.870 --> 00:53:21.400
So now, we have to go
back to our MO diagrams

00:53:21.400 --> 00:53:25.050
and figure out where to put
these new molecular orbitals

00:53:25.050 --> 00:53:27.550
onto our nice diagrams.

00:53:27.550 --> 00:53:32.440
And it's not as simple as
it was before because where

00:53:32.440 --> 00:53:37.630
we put these new sigma 2pz
molecular orbitals depends

00:53:37.630 --> 00:53:40.100
on what z is.

00:53:40.100 --> 00:53:44.800
So it depends on the value of z.

00:53:44.800 --> 00:53:49.840
So if z is less than
the magic number of 8,

00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:57.570
then we have our pi 2px and 2py
orbitals are lower in energy

00:53:57.570 --> 00:54:02.980
than our sigma 2pz
molecular orbital.

00:54:02.980 --> 00:54:09.250
But if we are equal
to or greater than 8,

00:54:09.250 --> 00:54:14.810
then the sigma 2pz
orbital is lower energy

00:54:14.810 --> 00:54:19.080
than the pi 2px and 2py.

00:54:19.080 --> 00:54:22.780
So less than 8, pi is first.

00:54:22.780 --> 00:54:27.560
It's lower in energy as you
go up your energy scale.

00:54:27.560 --> 00:54:32.710
And if z is equal to or
greater than 8, pi is second

00:54:32.710 --> 00:54:35.530
and sigma is first.

00:54:35.530 --> 00:54:37.390
So how are you going
to remember this?

00:54:37.390 --> 00:54:39.730
There could be many different
ways one can remember it,

00:54:39.730 --> 00:54:41.770
but I'll tell you
how I remember it.

00:54:41.770 --> 00:54:47.780
And my life revolves around
my daughter and my dog.

00:54:47.780 --> 00:54:51.260
And so at Thanksgiving, we
always have the question,

00:54:51.260 --> 00:54:53.980
can I eat pie first?

00:54:53.980 --> 00:54:58.430
So if you are
under the age of 8,

00:54:58.430 --> 00:55:02.530
you always want your pie first.

00:55:02.530 --> 00:55:08.120
So if z is less than
8, pi comes first.

00:55:08.120 --> 00:55:11.920
Pi is lower in energy
and sigma is higher.

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:15.670
However, when you mature
to the grand age of 9,

00:55:15.670 --> 00:55:19.280
say, or 10, if
you were a kid, 10

00:55:19.280 --> 00:55:21.090
is like the oldest
you can possibly

00:55:21.090 --> 00:55:23.480
imagine being, very mature.

00:55:23.480 --> 00:55:25.230
And you can eat your
Thanksgiving dinner

00:55:25.230 --> 00:55:26.700
and wait for pie.

00:55:26.700 --> 00:55:29.920
So that is how I
would remember it,

00:55:29.920 --> 00:55:34.230
under 8 pi is first,
equal to 8 or greater,

00:55:34.230 --> 00:55:36.650
you can wait till after
dinner to have your pie,

00:55:36.650 --> 00:55:38.710
pi comes second.

00:55:38.710 --> 00:55:42.010
Note that the ordering of
the antibonding orbitals

00:55:42.010 --> 00:55:45.440
is the same, so all
you have to remember

00:55:45.440 --> 00:55:53.420
is down here depends on z,
is pi first or is pi second?

00:55:53.420 --> 00:55:56.020
So let's take a
look at an example.

00:55:56.020 --> 00:55:59.090
Let's look at our friend
molecular oxygen that has a z

00:55:59.090 --> 00:56:00.650
equal to 8.

00:56:00.650 --> 00:56:05.310
So oxygen is at the
old, mature age of 8,

00:56:05.310 --> 00:56:08.710
and so it's going to
have its sigma 2pz first.

00:56:08.710 --> 00:56:12.520
It can wait for its pi
orbitals until later.

00:56:12.520 --> 00:56:15.130
So let's start putting
in our electrons.

00:56:15.130 --> 00:56:20.830
So we have each oxygen making
up molecular oxygen, or O2.

00:56:20.830 --> 00:56:26.570
Brings two 2s orbitals to the
Thanksgiving dinner table,

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:29.350
and two of them
go down in energy

00:56:29.350 --> 00:56:33.280
into the bonding sigma
2s orbital and two

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:38.750
go into our antibonding,
sigma star 2s orbital.

00:56:38.750 --> 00:56:44.940
Now, we have four
electrons in our atomic pz

00:56:44.940 --> 00:56:47.450
orbitals, four
from each molecule,

00:56:47.450 --> 00:56:50.010
so we need to put
all of those in.

00:56:50.010 --> 00:56:53.080
So we always start with
the lowest energy orbital.

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:55.980
So we'll put two in
there, then we'll go up.

00:56:55.980 --> 00:56:58.590
We have two more
here, two more here.

00:56:58.590 --> 00:57:02.050
We'll put them in singly
with their spins parallel,

00:57:02.050 --> 00:57:05.240
and then we'll pair them up
in the lowest energy orbitals.

00:57:05.240 --> 00:57:08.080
And then we have two
more left, so we're

00:57:08.080 --> 00:57:11.200
going to have to put those up
in our antibonding orbitals.

00:57:11.200 --> 00:57:18.570
So they go into pi 2px and
pi 2py star orbitals up here.

00:57:18.570 --> 00:57:19.090
All right.

00:57:19.090 --> 00:57:23.260
So now we can calculate
the bond order for oxygen,

00:57:23.260 --> 00:57:24.530
and that's a clicker question.

00:57:52.920 --> 00:57:53.420
All right.

00:57:53.420 --> 00:57:55.070
Let's just take 10 more seconds.

00:58:10.940 --> 00:58:12.360
All right.

00:58:12.360 --> 00:58:15.000
So let's take a look over here.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:19.120
So bond order, again,
is 1/2 the number

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:23.480
of bonding electrons minus
the number of antibonding

00:58:23.480 --> 00:58:25.250
electrons.

00:58:25.250 --> 00:58:30.280
And we have eight bonding--
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

00:58:30.280 --> 00:58:33.870
And we have four
antibonding-- 1, 2, 3, 4.

00:58:33.870 --> 00:58:36.830
So that gives us
a bond order of 2.

00:58:36.830 --> 00:58:38.452
And the bond order
equation is one

00:58:38.452 --> 00:58:39.660
that you do have to memorize.

00:58:39.660 --> 00:58:42.890
That will not be given
to you on an exam.

00:58:42.890 --> 00:58:47.670
And with a bond order of 2,
we have a pretty big number

00:58:47.670 --> 00:58:49.390
for dissociation energy.

00:58:49.390 --> 00:58:52.350
Again, that's energy you have
to put into a bond to break it,

00:58:52.350 --> 00:58:56.160
to dissociate it, and that
means it's a pretty strong bond

00:58:56.160 --> 00:58:57.290
if it's a big number.

00:58:57.290 --> 00:59:00.580
If you need a lot of energy,
that's a strong bond.

00:59:00.580 --> 00:59:03.880
Another thing that you
can see from this diagram

00:59:03.880 --> 00:59:07.080
is that O2 is a biradical.

00:59:07.080 --> 00:59:15.390
It has two lone pair electrons,
so two unpaired electrons,

00:59:15.390 --> 00:59:18.770
which also makes
it paramagnetic,

00:59:18.770 --> 00:59:21.240
or attracted to
a magnetic field.

00:59:21.240 --> 00:59:23.640
So whenever you have
unpaired electrons,

00:59:23.640 --> 00:59:26.050
you will have a
paramagnetic species,

00:59:26.050 --> 00:59:28.230
and diamagnetic means
they're all paired.

00:59:28.230 --> 00:59:31.200
And so there are some questions
on problem sets and on exams,

00:59:31.200 --> 00:59:33.490
so you need to know the
definitions of those.

00:59:33.490 --> 00:59:34.270
All right.

00:59:34.270 --> 00:59:37.050
So we talked about this when
we were doing Lewis structures,

00:59:37.050 --> 00:59:38.630
if you recall.

00:59:38.630 --> 00:59:42.700
And we drew a beautiful Lewis
structure of molecular oxygen

00:59:42.700 --> 00:59:46.950
that had two lone pairs on
each oxygen and a double bond.

00:59:46.950 --> 00:59:49.330
But I told you that
that was not really

00:59:49.330 --> 00:59:53.410
a complete description
of molecular oxygen,

00:59:53.410 --> 00:59:56.810
that molecular oxygen
was actually a biradical,

00:59:56.810 --> 01:00:00.360
but you would not get a hint of
that from the Lewis structure.

01:00:00.360 --> 01:00:05.030
So if you draw the Lewis
structure as a biradical,

01:00:05.030 --> 01:00:07.940
then you have a
single electron here

01:00:07.940 --> 01:00:10.830
and a single electron
there and a single bond.

01:00:10.830 --> 01:00:13.300
But we also see
the bond orders 2,

01:00:13.300 --> 01:00:16.930
so this one describes
the biradical nature,

01:00:16.930 --> 01:00:19.300
but doesn't really
describe that double bond

01:00:19.300 --> 01:00:20.860
character that it has.

01:00:20.860 --> 01:00:24.100
So neither of these Lewis
structures really completely

01:00:24.100 --> 01:00:28.460
describe molecular
oxygen. And we

01:00:28.460 --> 01:00:32.020
need our molecular orbital
diagram to really help

01:00:32.020 --> 01:00:36.080
us understand the properties
of molecular oxygen,

01:00:36.080 --> 01:00:38.330
that it's pretty
strong bond between it,

01:00:38.330 --> 01:00:42.920
it has double bond character,
but it also is very reactive.

01:00:42.920 --> 01:00:44.270
It's a biradical.

01:00:44.270 --> 01:00:46.710
So this is just a
bizarre molecule.

01:00:46.710 --> 01:00:51.000
And really that is why this
diagram right here really tells

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:55.120
us why our life, our
planet is what it is,

01:00:55.120 --> 01:00:57.720
right here, that describes it.

01:00:57.720 --> 01:01:00.230
It's because of
oxygen that we have

01:01:00.230 --> 01:01:01.920
the life forms that we did.

01:01:01.920 --> 01:01:03.960
Life was very different
on this planet

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:07.300
before molecular
oxygen came about.

01:01:07.300 --> 01:01:12.010
You did have microbes that lived
anaerobically without oxygen.

01:01:12.010 --> 01:01:15.040
But when oxygen came,
everything changed.

01:01:15.040 --> 01:01:19.900
And so if I say, can
you explain life to me?

01:01:19.900 --> 01:01:22.670
You can draw this,
and there it is.

01:01:22.670 --> 01:01:25.680
This explains life as
we know it because life

01:01:25.680 --> 01:01:30.980
as we know it exists because of
this crazy molecule that is O2,

01:01:30.980 --> 01:01:32.680
nothing else really like it.

01:01:32.680 --> 01:01:36.760
It is an amazing molecule
that allows us to live.

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:37.805
So there you go.

01:01:37.805 --> 01:01:40.180
I was going to say you don't
learn anything in chemistry.

01:01:40.180 --> 01:01:42.510
This diagram I
just explains life

01:01:42.510 --> 01:01:45.160
as we know it to
you, right there.

01:01:45.160 --> 01:01:47.450
All right.

01:01:47.450 --> 01:01:50.060
It's not just oxygen, there's a
few other elements that, yeah,

01:01:50.060 --> 01:01:51.601
are pretty important,
and one of them

01:01:51.601 --> 01:01:54.400
is nitrogen. We wouldn't
really be much anywhere

01:01:54.400 --> 01:01:55.960
without nitrogen either.

01:01:55.960 --> 01:01:59.920
Oxygen is, no, nitrogen
is pretty special too.

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:01.120
This also helps.

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:02.870
Maybe these two
molecular orbital

01:02:02.870 --> 01:02:05.450
diagrams really sum
up life as we know it.

01:02:05.450 --> 01:02:05.950
All right.

01:02:05.950 --> 01:02:10.280
So let's look at
molecular nitrogen, N2.

01:02:10.280 --> 01:02:14.750
So we have two electrons
in our 2s orbitals,

01:02:14.750 --> 01:02:16.610
so we're going to
bring them together.

01:02:16.610 --> 01:02:20.050
We're going to put two in the
lower energy orbital, our sigma

01:02:20.050 --> 01:02:23.820
2s, and two in our
antibonding orbital.

01:02:23.820 --> 01:02:26.580
And then we have three
in our p orbitals

01:02:26.580 --> 01:02:30.660
from this nitrogen, three
electrons from this nitrogen,

01:02:30.660 --> 01:02:32.890
and so we'll put them down here.

01:02:32.890 --> 01:02:36.510
We'll put in 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

01:02:36.510 --> 01:02:40.040
So we didn't need to use any
of these antibonding orbitals,

01:02:40.040 --> 01:02:43.190
and this is a z
less than 8 case.

01:02:43.190 --> 01:02:45.900
So here we have our
pi orbitals first

01:02:45.900 --> 01:02:50.520
because it is z less than 8.

01:02:50.520 --> 01:02:53.760
So let's look at
the bond order here.

01:02:53.760 --> 01:02:59.735
And the bond order is 1/2
of 8-- 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7,

01:02:59.735 --> 01:03:03.720
8-- eight bonding
electrons and just

01:03:03.720 --> 01:03:09.930
these two antibonding electrons,
so 1/2 of 8 minus 2 is 3.

01:03:09.930 --> 01:03:13.740
And you have a really big number
for your dissociation energy,

01:03:13.740 --> 01:03:15.680
941.

01:03:15.680 --> 01:03:18.300
This is a very stable
molecule, and you

01:03:18.300 --> 01:03:22.900
can draw the Lewis structure of
this without much difficulty.

01:03:22.900 --> 01:03:26.330
This one works quite well,
and you get a triple bond

01:03:26.330 --> 01:03:28.530
and two lone pairs.

01:03:28.530 --> 01:03:30.780
So this would be a
diamagnetic molecule,

01:03:30.780 --> 01:03:35.300
no unpaired electrons,
no radicals here.

01:03:35.300 --> 01:03:38.740
But this is a
crazy, strong bond.

01:03:38.740 --> 01:03:42.530
It's really hard
to split nitrogen

01:03:42.530 --> 01:03:44.500
because of this triple bond.

01:03:44.500 --> 01:03:47.190
And molecular orbital
theory tells you

01:03:47.190 --> 01:03:48.770
it should be its triple bond.

01:03:48.770 --> 01:03:52.440
It should be really,
really strong interactions

01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:53.816
between these nitrogens.

01:03:53.816 --> 01:03:55.190
And so this is a
very hard thing.

01:03:55.190 --> 01:03:56.856
We want to do is
industrially, and we'll

01:03:56.856 --> 01:03:59.480
talk more about this when we
get a chemical equilibrium.

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:02.110
How do you split
the nitrogen bond.

01:04:02.110 --> 01:04:06.060
This is actually, currently,
a big area of research,

01:04:06.060 --> 01:04:09.036
how you break that bond because
we need nitrogen for life.

01:04:09.036 --> 01:04:10.160
And so how do you split it?

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:12.840
There's lots of nitrogen
N2 in the atmosphere,

01:04:12.840 --> 01:04:16.010
but we need it here,
and we need it usable,

01:04:16.010 --> 01:04:18.580
so we need to break
that bond to use it.

01:04:18.580 --> 01:04:20.670
So we'll come back to this
in chemical equilibrium

01:04:20.670 --> 01:04:23.920
